summary:
Internationalism is part of who I am as a bilingual Canadian who grew up in English and French cultures. I also hold Hungarian citizenship. My background on two continents and my unique autobiography will help me to address the needs of multinational work environments. I am an experienced researcher with broad interests in culture, history, politics, film, and queer studies. 

At Leiden University, I have supported the LUCAS community in innovative ways both inside and outside the classroom. I have diversified my teaching methods through the incorporation of group presentations in each course. In doing so, I have found a creative opportunity to fully enhance student engagement with the curriculum. Most importantly, I have hosted shared film screenings on campus to help build the scholarly community and establish a new forum for dialogue between the lecturer and the students.  

At Erasmus University Rotterdam, At Erasmus University Rotterdam, in the BA thesis course within Media and Communication, I guided my students to better understand the critical role of qualitative empirical research within media studies and helped them to enhance their writing skills. My duties also included the thesis supervision of MA candidates. In that role, I mentored these students in the creation of achievable and exciting research projects. I have worked with today’s students to translate their passions into scholarship.
